Beat incantations, to transglobal questions of tribe and verse at the century's close, Lincoln shows where we mine the mother lode of New World voices, what distinguishes American verse, which tales our poets sing and what inflections we hear in the rhythms, pitches, and parsings of native lines.Lincoln presents the Lakota concept of "singing with the heart of a bear" as poetry which moves through an artist. He argues for a fusion of estranged cultures, tribal and émigré, margin and mainstream, in detailing the ethnopoetics of Native American translation and the growing modernist concern for a "native" sense of the "makings" of American verse. This fascinating work represents a major new effort in understanding American and Native American literature, spirituality, and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAmerican poetryxIndian authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican poetryxIndian influences. 0aIndians in literature. 0aIndians of North AmericaxIntellectual life. 7aPOETRY / General.2bisacsh  aamerican indian.  aamerican literature.  aamerican poetry.  aamerican verse.  abible.  abiblical.  acontemporary poetry.  aculture.  aethnicity.  aethnopoetics.  afree verse.  agender studies.  agender.  agreenwich village.  aindigenous people.  aindigenous.  alakota.  aliterary analysis.  aliterary criticism.  alost garden.  amodernist.  amythology.  anative american literature.  anative american.  anative literature.  anew world.  apoetic criticism.  apoetic verse.  apoetry analysis.  apoetry studies.  arenaissance.  aspirituality.  atranslation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021890140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520922952?locatt=mode:legac